## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## UNIT NUMBER EXTRACTION + BUILDING MEMORY
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
##
## PROBLEM:
## Driver has to open Speed X app at each stop to get the unit/apt number
## because UNIT either drops it during scan or doesn't show it prominently.
## Unit numbers ARE on the Speed X label — this is a parsing + display problem.
##
## THE FIX — 3 layers:
##
## LAYER 1 — FIX SCAN PARSING (catch it at warehouse, not at the door)
##
##   In the Claude Vision / Tesseract address extraction logic:
##   - Always extract unit/apt number as a SEPARATE field from street address
##   - Patterns to detect: Apt, Apt., APT, Unit, UNIT, #, Suite, Ste, Fl, Floor
##     plus bare numbers after a comma (e.g. "123 Main St, 4B")
##   - Store in stops.unit column (already exists in DB schema)
##   - Display the unit number PROMINENTLY on every stop card:
##       - On scan page: shown as a separate orange badge next to the address
##       - On dashboard stop list: shown below address, never hidden
##       - On stop_active delivery screen: LARGE at top, impossible to miss
##
##   - During scan phase: if address is a known multi-unit building
##     (building exists in buildings table OR address_intel shows multiple
##     unit numbers for same street address) AND no unit number was extracted:
##     FLAG IT IMMEDIATELY with a yellow warning card:
##     "No unit number found for [address] — this looks like a multi-unit building.
##      Enter it now before you leave."
##     Driver fills it in once at warehouse. Never discovers it mid-route.
##
## LAYER 2 — BUILDING MEMORY (never ask twice)
##
##   Extend address_intel table:
##   - ALTER TABLE address_intel ADD COLUMN known_units TEXT DEFAULT '[]'
##     (JSON array of unit numbers seen at this address)
##   - Every time a stop is delivered with a unit number confirmed:
##     append that unit number to known_units for that address
##   - On future scans: if same street address with no unit number extracted,
##     AND known_units has entries: show a quick-pick list of known units
##     so driver taps the right one instead of typing
##
##   For brand new addresses with no unit number:
##   - On stop_active screen, if unit field is empty AND building table
##     suggests multi-unit (or address contains keywords: apt, suite, bldg):
##     show a one-tap prompt at arrival: "Unit number? (saves for next time)"
##     Driver enters it once -> saved to address_intel.known_units forever
##
## LAYER 3 — STOP ACTIVE SCREEN (unit number front and center)
##
##   On the stop_active.html delivery screen:
##   - Unit number displayed in its own large block at the top, styled like:
##       APT / UNIT
##       [ 4B ]    <- large, bold, high contrast
##   - If unit number is missing: show a red "No unit #" badge with
##     a tap-to-add button right there — no app switching needed
##   - Unit number should be the first thing the driver sees when they
##     pull up the stop, not buried in the address string
##
## FILES TO TOUCH:
##   - app.py: update address extraction to parse unit as separate field,
##     add known_units column to address_intel, update deliver endpoint
##     to save confirmed unit to address_intel
##   - templates/scan.html: show unit badge, flag missing units on multi-unit
##   - templates/stop_active.html: large unit number display at top
##   - templates/driver_dashboard.html: show unit number on stop cards
##
## DO NOT CHANGE:
##   - stops.unit column already exists - just populate and display it better
##   - address_intel table - only ADD columns, don't restructure
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## RESIDENT PHONE AUTO-MATCH + ONE-TIME CAPTURE
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
##
## PROBLEM:
## Driver has to open Speed X app at every stop to get the customer phone number.
## Speed X doesn't put phone numbers on the label. It lives inside their app.
## UNIT needs to eliminate this lookup entirely.
##
## THE FIX — 2 layers:
##
## LAYER 1 — AUTO-MATCH ON DELIVERY (zero effort when resident is known)
##
##   When a stop is loaded in stop_active.html:
##   - Query residents table: match on address + unit number
##     SELECT * FROM residents WHERE address LIKE ? AND unit = ?
##     (fuzzy match on address — strip apt/unit suffix before comparing)
##   - If match found AND resident.phone is not null:
##     -> Phone number is pre-filled on the stop. SMS send button is live.
##     -> Show resident name + phone at top of stop screen
##     -> "On the way" SMS fires automatically when driver hits Start on that stop
##     -> No lookup, no switching apps, no typing
##   - Also match on customer_name from the scan if address match is ambiguous
##     (some buildings have multiple residents)
##
## LAYER 2 — ONE-TIME CAPTURE PROMPT (10 seconds, saves forever)
##
##   When stop_active loads and NO resident phone is found:
##   - Show a non-blocking prompt card on the stop screen:
##
##       [ Add customer phone? ]  <- tappable card, not a modal
##       "No number on file for this address.
##        Add it once — UNIT remembers it forever."
##       [ phone input field ]  [ Save & Notify ]
##
##   - Card sits below the address/navigation section, doesn't block delivery flow
##   - Driver can skip it (X button) and deliver without a number
##   - If driver enters the number:
##     -> Save to residents table (address, unit, phone, customer_name from stop)
##     -> Immediately send "on the way" SMS
##     -> That address is now permanently in the system
##   - Input is tel type, numeric keyboard opens automatically on iOS
##   - After Save: card collapses, confirmation shows "Saved. SMS sent."
##
## BUILDING UP OVER TIME:
##   - Every delivery where driver adds a number populates residents table
##   - QR code scans from building flyers also populate residents table
##   - Both sources merge — same table, same auto-match logic
##   - After 2-3 weeks of routes: most frequent addresses pre-filled
##   - After 1-2 months: Speed X phone lookup is completely obsolete
##
## DASHBOARD INDICATOR:
##   - On driver_dashboard.html stop list: show a phone icon on stops
##     where a resident phone is already on file (green = has number,
##     grey = no number yet)
##   - Gives driver a visual heads-up before they even leave the warehouse
##     which stops will need the manual capture step
##
## BACKEND:
##   - No new tables needed — residents table already has phone, address, unit
##   - Add helper function: get_resident_for_stop(stop_id) — returns resident
##     or None. Used by stop_active route and dashboard route.
##   - On stop_active POST (deliver): if phone submitted in form, upsert resident
##   - Pass resident object to stop_active.html template
##
## DO NOT CHANGE:
##   - Existing resident portal or QR signup flow
##   - SMS sending logic (Textbelt/Twilio) — just wire it to the auto-match
##   - residents table schema — only INSERT/UPDATE, no structural changes
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## CRITICAL BUG FIXES — ZONE STABILITY + BAG REMOVAL
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
##
## BUG 1 — REMOVE BAG_SIZE ENTIRELY
##
##   What it does: BAG_SIZE = 8 sub-divides each zone into "bags" of 8 stops.
##   Zone A becomes A-Bag1, A-Bag2, etc. Director X sees this as confusing
##   "groups of 10" that make no sense after he's already physically loaded
##   packages by zone into his vehicle.
##
##   THE FIX:
##   - Delete the BAG_SIZE constant (line ~1142 in app.py)
##   - Remove all bag_num and bag_label fields from build_optimized_route()
##   - Remove all bag_num and bag_label fields from any other route build functions
##   - Search entire app.py for bag_num, bag_label, BAG_SIZE, n_bags, bag_group
##     and remove every reference
##   - Remove bag display from ALL templates:
##       scan.html, driver_dashboard.html, route_detail.html, stop_active.html
##     Search templates for bag_num, bag_label, Bag1, Bag2, n_bags
##   - Packages belong to ZONES only. No sub-grouping within zones. Period.
##
## BUG 2 — ZONES ARE SEQUENTIAL CHUNKS, NOT GEOGRAPHIC K-MEANS
##
##   What's happening: build_optimized_route() assigns zones using:
##     zone_seq = min(si // zone_size, k - 1)
##   This makes Zone A = stops 1-20, Zone B = stops 21-40 (sequential chunking).
##   K-means IS defined in the codebase (kmeans_geo function exists) but is
##   NEVER CALLED during the actual route build. This is the root cause of
##   zones changing — the dashboard falls back to scan_items.zone_letter
##   which was assigned before optimization, giving totally different zones
##   than what was physically loaded.
##
##   THE FIX:
##   In build_optimized_route(), after OSRM orders the stops:
##
##   REPLACE:
##     zone_size = max(1, math.ceil(n_stops / k)) if n_stops else 1
##     ...zone_seq = min(si // zone_size, k - 1)...
##
##   WITH:
##     1. Run kmeans_geo(routable, k) on the geocoded stop coordinates
##     2. Assign zone_letter based on cluster index (cluster 0 = A, 1 = B, etc.)
##     3. Sort clusters geographically (furthest from depot = Zone A,
##        closest to depot = last zone) so loading order still makes sense
##     4. Within each geographic zone, order stops by OSRM delivery sequence
##     5. zone_letter is now geography-based, not sequence-based
##
##   ZONE LOCK RULE (already in architecture, must be enforced in code):
##   - Once route is built and zones assigned: zone_letter is written to
##     stops table and NEVER recalculated again for that route
##   - build_route_zone_context() must ONLY READ zone_letter from stops table
##     It must NOT fall back to scan_items.zone_letter after optimize
##     Remove this block from build_route_zone_context():
##       if s.get('tracking') and (not s.get('scan_order') or not s.get('zone_letter')):
##           item = db.execute("SELECT scan_order, zone_letter FROM scan_items...")
##     If zone_letter is missing from stops after optimize, that is a build bug
##     to fix at build time — not something to paper over with a fallback
##
##   RESULT:
##   - Zones are geographic (all addresses in one neighborhood = same zone)
##   - Zones NEVER change after optimize is hit
##   - What driver sees on dashboard = exactly what they loaded into the car
##   - Zero zone drift during the route
##
## IMPLEMENTATION ORDER FOR THESE FIXES:
##   1. Remove BAG_SIZE first (safest, purely additive removal)
##   2. Fix zone assignment to use kmeans_geo
##   3. Remove scan_items fallback from build_route_zone_context
##   4. Test: optimize a route, note zone assignments, refresh dashboard
##      mid-route — zones must be identical
##
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## Do Not Touch
- Vehicle zone definitions (suv_midsize confirmed correct)
- Claude Vision address extraction logic (extend it, don't rewrite it)
- OSRM fallback logic (keep as fallback when Google Maps key is absent)

## Constants
- ZONE_LOCK_THRESHOLD = 20 (legacy — being phased out)
- ZONE_STABLE_MILES = 0.15mi
- Detroit ZIP codes are primary operating area (e.g. 48202 ~3.3mi → ~4 zones)

## Key Context
- This is a real production tool used daily by Speed X drivers
- Speed and reliability matter more than polish
- Director X uses this personally — UX must be frictionless
- No redundancy in workflow — every interaction must have a purpose
